		<title>Star Catcher Industries Secures $65M for Space Grid</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/star-catcher-industries-secures-65m-for-space-grid/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ekemini]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 12 May 2026 17:11:40 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=201100</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Star Catcher Industries has closed a $65 million oversubscribed Series A investment. This will fund a project that sounds more like science fiction: the world&#8217;s first orbital energy grid. B</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/star-catcher-industries-secures-65m-for-space-grid/" data-wpel-link="internal">Star Catcher Industries Secures $65M for Space Grid</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.star-catcher.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Star Catcher Industries</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> has closed a $65 million oversubscribed Series A </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/elliptic-raises-120m-from-nasdaq-ventures-and-deutsche-bank/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">investment</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. This will fund a project that sounds more like science fiction: the world&#8217;s first orbital energy grid. </span>B Capital hosted this funding round, co-led by Shield Capital and Cerberus Ventures, with contributions from GreatPoint Ventures, Helena, Oceans Ventures, and MVP Ventures. The Florida-based firm has now raised an impressive $88 million in just the last two years.&#8221;</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Solving the Power Budget Problem</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">For decades, satellite operators have been limited by power budgets. To function, a satellite must rely on its own solar panels, which are often limited by size, weight, and the inevitable time spent in the Earth’s shadow (eclipse).</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Star Catcher’s solution is an energy infrastructure layer in Low Earth Orbit (LEO). The company plans to deploy a network of power nodes, spacecraft designed specifically to harvest solar energy and beam it directly to other satellites using concentrated optical power beaming.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_201102" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-201102" class="size-large wp-image-201102" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/view-of-the-earth-1024x682.jpg" alt="view of the earth" width="1024" height="682" /><p id="caption-attachment-201102" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Fundamentally, our vision is to make it as easy to operate in space as it is on Earth,&#8221; said Andrew Rush, co-founder and CEO of Star Catcher. &#8220;We want to take the industry from a world of power scarcity to a world of power abundance.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/elliptic-raises-120m-from-nasdaq-ventures-and-deutsche-bank/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Elliptic Raises $120M From Nasdaq Ventures and Deutsche Bank</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">No Retrofits Required</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">One of the most disruptive aspects of Star Catcher’s technology is that it requires no hardware modifications on the part of the customer. The system is designed to beam energy to the triple-junction solar cells already standard on most commercial and government satellites.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">By concentrating broad-spectrum energy onto these existing arrays, Star Catcher claims it can provide satellites with up to 10 times more power than they could generate on their own. This allows smaller, cheaper satellites to perform high-energy tasks like advanced sensing, high-bandwidth communications or complex edge computing that was previously reserved for massive, billion-dollar platforms.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Strategic Board Appointments</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The funding round also brings significant geopolitical and military expertise to Star Catcher’s leadership. Joining the company’s board are:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>General John W. “Jay” Raymond (Ret.)</b><span style="font-weight: 400">, the former and first Chief of Space Operations for the U.S. Space Force.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Jeff Johnson</b><span style="font-weight: 400">, General Partner and Global Head of Energy at B Capital.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>David Rothzeid</b><span style="font-weight: 400">, Principal at Shield Capital.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The inclusion of General Raymond signals a strong focus on national security. The ability to beam power to manoeuvring satellites or to jump-start spacecraft that have suffered power failures is a high-priority capability for the U.S. Department of Defence.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Traction and T-Minus Zero</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Star Catcher is more than just an idea. It is already a record-breaker. In late 2025, the company managed to transmit 1.1 kilowatts of power over an unprecedented 100 metres at NASA’s Kennedy Space Center. This broke the previous record set by DARPA.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Already in its commercial pipeline, with $3 billion in annual revenue, and having signed seven power purchase agreements, this company has plans to move quickly. The Series A investment will fund the company&#8217;s first orbital power-beaming demonstration, scheduled for launch later this year. Next, the company intends to deploy its entire fleet of 200 power nodes to service space, permanently establishing a scalable utility in orbit.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/star-catcher-industries-secures-65m-for-space-grid/" data-wpel-link="internal">Star Catcher Industries Secures $65M for Space Grid</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
